Commentary.Commentary: Onto the Windies batters now, that is the area which is a cause of concern for them and they are up against a very potent pace attack and on a wicket which is doing a bit. Will they be up for the challenge or will South Africa dominate with the ball? We will find out.

Windies, at the start on Day 1, struggled with their lines and lengths. They were either too full or too short which let the openers score freely. However, they found their lines and lengths as the game progressed and their bowlers were rewarded. Alzarri Joseph was the pick with a fifer. He bowled with pace and he's the reason for the Windies making a come back in the game.

Except for the first over, West Indies will be pleased with how things went about this morning. They will also be pleased they have kept the hosts to below 350. Let me remind you, at one stage, 400-plus looked on the cards for the hosts. South Africa were 221 for 1 thanks to a ton from Markram and a half ton from Elgar but once the two openers fell, no other batter managed to cross the 30-run mark. It was thanks to the lower-order they got close to the 350-run mark but it is still a competitive score.

South Africa HAVE BEEN BOWLED OUT FOR 342!
Commentary.Howout: c Tagenarine Chanderpaul b Alzarri Joseph

Time for the action to begin! The Windies players make their way out to the middle and they are followed by Gerald Coetzee and Marco Jansen who will resume their innings.

A fightback towards the second half of the day saw the Windies get back into the game. South Africa however, still have a decent score on the board and are not done yet. They would hope for the tail to wag and get them over thr 350-run mark. West Indies on the other hand, will want to make quick work of the remaining two wickets. An important first session coming up.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

From 221/1 to 300/8, West Indies will feel they have done a fantastic job here. The first two sessions were too wayward for them, the runs were flowing easily but it has to be the Alzarri Joseph over where the Windies got two tickets and then there was no stopping. The pitch started to help in the later stages as the other seamers got a wicket as well at least. Alzarri Joseph easily was the best of the lot. In the end, the light was not good enough but West Indies will be happy with how things panned out. Now then, West Indies will look to take the remaining wickets quickly on Day 2. Join us back at 1330 IST (0800 GMT) and earlier for all the build up. Till then, cheers.

South Africa won the toss and chose to bat which turned out to be a good decision as Dean Elgar and Aiden Markram joined hands to give a commendable start. Elgar fell after his fifty but Aiden Markram looked solid and posted his century. Tony de Zorzi too on his debut looked superb but got out on a disappointing note. Since then, South Africa sort of tumbled over and wickets kept falling away. Jansen is key now for South Africa to reach even 350 from here.

The umpire brings out the light-meter and feels the light is not good enough. That will be STUMPS. If South Africa started well, it is West Indies who will be the happier team in the end. What a session for them. The last session has helped them end the day on an even note.

...Day 1, Session 3...

Roston Chase and Alzarri Joseph were decent. West Indies will hope the final session brings some joy and wickets for them. They need the final session to go their way or else Aiden Markram is looking for a very big score here.

The debutant De Zorzi joined in the middle and he looks in control of his innings from the stand. The stand with Aiden Markram now moves to 65 and South Africa will hope for more.

Windies have bowled decently but in parts! They have been far too many boundary deliveries and they will hope they can tighten things up after the break. They will need to be patient, the wicket is not offering a lot. The key after the break will be to hit the right lines and lengths on consistent basis. Can they fight back after the interval?

That is a top, top session for South Africa! Bavuma will be a happy man so far, he wont the toss, elected to bat and the openers have laid a really good foundation for them to score big. It was testing earlier on where the ball did do a bit. Elgar did get a life but once the ball lost its shine, batting got easy and the two have cashed in. Elgar has crossed his half ton and Markram is looking to get to his. More of the same is what South Africa will want.

TOSS - South Africa have won the toss and ELECTED TO BAT!

West Indies have a stiff task ahead. Beating South Africa in Africa is never easy. They though come into this game on the back of a win against Zimbabwe but this is a lot tougher challenge. For now, let us just hope, they can be competitive enough. Stay tuned for the toss.

It is time for the first Test between South Africa and the Windies. With India being 2-0 up, South Africa's chances of reaching the WTC final is more or less over. They though would still be eager to win this series especially after the hammering they received against Australia. Also, it is the start of a new reign for them under the captaincy of Temba Bavuma.
... MATCH DAY ...
We are back. The players are out in the middle. Kemar Roach to start with the ball..
...THIRD INNINGS....

The hosts hung in there. They were disciplined throughout and the pitch started to help in the final session which resulted to wickets after wickets. Kagiso Rabada started things while Anrich Nortje kept hunting with his pace from the other end. The speedster took a five-fer while Rabada and Gerald Coetzee took four together. Now then! South Africa have a handy lead. It is a very tough patch to play. Around 12 overs remaining. Can South Africa end without losing any wickets?

A lead of 130 runs for South Africa. That was some turnaround by the home team. A splendid performance by them with the ball and have to say, the final session on both days have been the most entertaining one. 7 wickets fall in this one. Just like South Africa, West Indies fall like a pack of cards. From 169 for 3 to 212 all-out. The second half didn't perform to their potential. At one stage, West Indies were stubborn and looked like will easily cut off the run. Jermaine Blackwood batted decently. Raymon Reifer scored a sensible fifty and there were contributions from couple of others as well but then came the Tea-break and after that it was all South Africa.

We saw on Day 1 how wickets started to tumble over and South Africa will hope for something similar. The pitch does tend to assist the seamers later in the day and the Proteas will have that in mind. Nothing to separate as of now. All eyes on the last session of Day 2 which is coming up soon.

The session started with Reifer and Jermaine Blackwood posting a solid stand. Jermaine Blackwood looked very strong with his defense but Anrich Nortje got better of him.

South Africa will be slightly disappointed with the amount of boundary balls they have bvowled but will be happy with the two wickets they have got. Also, there have been encouraging signs as the ball has moved around and the key for them will be to stick to the right lines and lengths. An interesting session awaits.

A good session of Test cricket! Have to say, South Africa are ahead in the game but West Indies will not be very disappointed with how things stand at the moment. First they managed to bowl South Africa out quickly this morning and then have scored freely in their reply. They did lose Kraigg Brathwaite early but Tagenarine Chanderpaul and Raymon Reifer batted well after that. They would have loved to have headed into Lunch one down but they lost Tagenarine Chanderpaul late in the session. Jermaine Blackwood though has looked positive after walking out and the Windies will hope these two can build a good stand.

For South Africa, except for Markram no other batter crossed the 30-run mark. 7 of their batters were dismissed for a score below 10. However, thanks to their bowlers, they had a healthy lead in the first innings and courtesy that, they have set a stiff target in front of the Windies. It is just short of 250 and with the amount of movement we have seen, South Africa will beack themselves to defend it. Windies on the other hand, know they do have a chance to chase it down if they bat well. They though will need to play one over out and they would hope they do not lose a wicket in that.

Top, top performance from West Indies and their bowlers have kept their side in the game. They needed wickets quickly today morning and they have taken just less than one session to do so. Also, they have managed to keep the lead under 250. Roach was the star for them on Day 3 as he ended with a fifer but overall, it was a complete performance from their bowlers. Brilliant.

The first session could well dictate which way this game is heading towards. If Windies manage to take wickets quickly, they would feel they will have a chance but if the hosts manage to get a good partnership, they can well and truly move well ahead of the game. The hosts will yet again rely on the likes of Markram who is well set and hope he can find an able partner. Windies on the other hand, need to hit the right lines and lengths right from the word go.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

That lead could well prove to be vital as South Africa have lost 4 in quick succession. The lead is still a healthy one and they have their star from the first innings still out there. One good stand is what they'll be hoping for as anything above 300 won't be an easy chase. Aiden Markram will be key for the home team. Windies on the other hand, need to continue what they did in the last session. They would be desperately wanting to chase something below 250. Can they keep the hosts under that? We will find out. Join us back at 1330 IST (8 am GMT) and earlier for the build up. Cheers!

The story could have been a lot different had the Windies middle order fired. They were in a good position at 169 for 3 but then wickets fell in heaps. Nortje was the star and helped his side gain a big lead with his five-fer.

Yet another excellent day of cricket and this game is turning out to be an exciting one, especially after the bowling performance by Windies in the last session. When South Africa got a big lead, it seemed like they would run away with the game but the Windies have fought back but the advantage still lies with the hosts.

Keegan Petersen knew it. Out it is. That will be the final ball. Stumps.

That is it from this game. South Africa take the lead. West Indies now have more time to check what went wrong. These two will meet again on the 8th of this month at 1300 IST (0800 GMT).  Do join us early for the build. Cheers!

Aiden Markram is the Player of the Match. He says it was nice to win. Adds he loves to bat on top and credits the staff for backing him. Shares he has played a lot of cricket here and is grateful to get some runs on this tough wicket. Reckons the pitch starts slow but opens up as the game progresses.

Temba Bavuma says it feels good to win. Adds it was crazy how it end but they did well to put up a respectable total to defend. Reckons they didn't get much partnership but Aiden Markram batted well and felt 300 runs would have been a good score but in the end 250 proved to be a lot. Shares they will rest well but also prepare well for the next game.

Kraigg Brathwaite says they missed out with the bat, it is not good enough to bat under 100 overs in both innings. Adds some balls were keeping it low, he feels there was lot for the bowlers but could have done better with the bat. Reckons it was a top effort from the bowlers in the second innings and hopes to come better in the next game. Says they have to be more mentally prepared. Applauds the performance of Alzarri Joseph and Kemar Roach in the end.
...Presentation time...

The start was superb by the home team. Dean Elgar and Aiden Markram laid up a good foundation. It looked like South Africa will score around 400 but the final session of Day 1 saw them crumbling down and losing their foot. Alzarri Joseph ended with a five-fer. It was sort of same for the Windies. Raymon Reifer batted well with a couple of contributions from others but just like hosts, lost it in the final session of Day 2. This time it was Anrich Nortje with a five-fer. The way pitch was playing, it shows how valuable the knock from Aiden Markram was in the second innings. Jermaine Blackwood tried to replicate the same but to no avail.

West Indies had less than 250 to chase this down but were put under serious pressure by some pace bowling of Rabada. No one apart from Jermaine Blackwood turned up for the chase. Joshua Da Silva and Jason Holder showed some intent but lost their wickets and once Blackwood fell, it was over for West Indies. If only there was some contribution from top order. West Indies would have given a tough fight.

South Africa take the lead in the two-match series. The game started to heat up in the third session. We saw most wickets fell on the final session of Day 1 and Day 2. South Africa had a 130-odd runs lead at the end of Day 2 and Aiden Markram was key on both innings. A splendid century in the first innings and a valuable 47 in the second with a key cameo from Gerald Coetzee to put a par score to defend.

A fantastic win by South Africa. This game went full throttle as it progressed. Who thought this match will end so quickly but that's how the pitch was playing. It was a beauty for the bowlers to bowl and South Africa came up on top in each session.

South Africa will smell a victory here as we have seen on Day 1 and Day 2 how wickets start to open up. They just need four and this is a good time for the pacers to take a much needed break and recharge themselves. Will we see a result in this final session?

The situation is simple here, South Africa need four wickets while West Indies need 154 runs to win. How fast the game has progressed? We have seen wickets falls so quickly but Blackwood has keep the hopes alive single-handedly with his counterattacking approach. He is past his fifty.
